Bengali
(Calcutta colloquial)
[Stress is not strong. Such stress as there is falls on the first
syllables of words of more than one syllable, except when shown
elsewhere, p, t, etc., without following h are unaspirated. t, d are
dental, j represents a sound between J and s. c, j are affricates
corresponding to this, h is voiced (= 11) except in ph, th, [h, kh,
ch. The italic j is a linking sound not occurring in the normal forms
of the words in which it is written; for instance the word here
written j ar would be pronounced ar in isolation, ae, ao, oe are
diphthongs. When v is not written, as in Jomoe, the vowels form two
syllables. £ = Et (se).]
